><span id=3D"yiv1296290291yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141">Namaste friends,<=
br> <br>Someone with psychiatric problems may expereience what sounds =
like a Kundalini rise, but it may or may not be one.<br> <br>It must b=
e conceded though that Kundalini spontaneously rising through various nadis=
 without one having gone through proper preparation in this life (i.e. fine=
-tuning of one's attitude and development of detachment) CAN create havoc!<=
br> <br>One may wonder how Kundalini may spontaneously rise in a layma=
n with no sadhana, while many serious sadhakas may not experience it.<br>&n=
bsp;<br>Firstly, Kundalini rise is NOT an achievement. It is just A SMALL S=
TEP in overcoming one's current limited identity.<br> <br>Let me give =
an analogy. One wanting to move from one's small dilapidated house (this bo=
dy-mind complex) to a huge palace (realized Self) may first construct the p=
alace over time and
 move into it when it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one =
occasionally goes and stays in the palace still under construction (analogy=
 for out of body experiences due to Kundalini rise), is it an achievement? =
In fact, it comes with risks. The former approach is safer and one loses no=
thing in it. Similarly, one can progress towards complete Self-realization =
without any out of body experiences. These are not my word's, but Maharshi =
Vasishtha's words to Lord Rama.<br> <br>Secondly, one does not get som=
ething without wanting it and putting sufficient effort towards it. One may=
 have deeply desired a Kundalini rise in a previous life and may have put e=
nough effort. As a result, one may be getting it now. But one may be unprep=
ared (and ironically may not even want it!) when it comes in this life.<br>=
 <br>As you do sadhana, try not to fancy too many specific desires. Na=
ture has a delay mechanism in granting your desires (because of constraints=
 on what
 Nature can give you right now, arising from YOUR OWN previous act=
ions). So Nature sometimes gives you what you want LATE, when you no longer=
 want it or want something else. For example, one may pray for great wealth=
 one's whole life and be born as a rich but very sick man in next life. One=
 may not enjoy that wealth and pray whole life for health. In the life afte=
r that, one may be very healthy, but not have any knowledge or money. </spa=
n><span id=3D"yiv1296290291yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141">In another case,=
 one may deeply desire to act in a famous film. One may be reborn as a tige=
r or a dog and act in a famous film, but not really enjoy that experience. =
Basically, people </span><span id=3D"yiv1296290291yui_3_7_2_19_136206784661=
9_141">keep going in circles through various lives, always "seeking" someth=
ing they are "missing".<br> <br>Anyway, coming back to Kundalini, if o=
ne deeply desires an out of body experience given by a rising Kundalini and=
 one's
 previous karmas constrain one from having it in THIS life, one may =
be born in next life with this specific desire destined to fructify (if the=
re is enough karmik force behind it).<br> <br>*    =
;    *        *<br> =
<br>Kundalini rise is not necessarily scary or painful, if one is well-prep=
ared in terms of attitude and detachment.<br> <br>Once I saw a chipmun=
k glued to a mouse trap. I went to free it and it panicked so badly and sta=
rted to shake violently. I went to save it from a certain slow death and it=
 was scared that I would kill it!<br> <br>We are like that chipmunk, g=
lued to the mouse trap called this body-mind complex and scared of being re=
scued from a certain slow death!<br> <br>If our ideas about who we are=
 (viz this current body-mind complex) are incorrect and if we are this "inf=
inite Self" as shastras say, won't a complete realization of that at some
 =
stage involve stepping out of this body-mind complex, without being scared?=
<br> <br>*        *  &nbs=
p;     *<br> <br>Kundalini rise after most undesir=
able conditioning is overcome, is far better than Kundalini rise forced whe=
n some really undesirable conditioning is still left in one's system.<br>&n=
bsp;<br>When one transcends one problematic notion about who one is and wha=
t one needs, another notion that lay buried deeper in consciousness may spr=
ing to the surface and torment one. If one overcomes the notion "I am the b=
ody", there may be another notion in one's body-mind complex that one's awa=
reness clings on to (</span><span id=3D"yiv1296290291yui_3_7_2_19_136206784=
6619_141"><span class=3D"yiv1296290291userContent">e.g. a great doctor, a g=
reat leader, a great scholar, a great saint etc</span>). As an extreme exam=
ple, if one person had a hidden deep desire to be a great soul who
 rescues=

 the world, he may fancy that he is a re-incarnated X or Y who will rescue=
 the world now. When one's self-awareness (i.e. Kundalini!) deeply clings t=
o any such notion, it can cause havoc. The person may show some signs of pr=
ogress and yet remain in ignorance and get stuck badly.<br> <br>An awa=
kened Kundalini in a system with undesirable conditioning may accentuate on=
e's weaknesses and wrong notions heavily and cause serious psychiatric and =
spiritual problems.<br> <br>*       =
; *        *<br> <br id=3D"yiv12962=
90291yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_158">The best approach I recommend is to NO=
T think in terms of Kundalini and its rise. Just do sadhana, overcome your =
weaknesses and improve your detachment over time. Again, I want to emphasiz=
e that detachment is not disgust or distaste for life/things/people around =
you. Disgust is the other side of coin of attachment.</span> It is a
 negat=
ive attachment.  </div> 
